00:12:45.521 --> 00:12:46.770
MARTHA ORTIZ: I read the book.

00:12:46.770 --> 00:12:50.961
I think it's the most celebrated
Spanish book, you know--

00:12:50.961 --> 00:12:52.460
SPEAKER: "Like Water
for Chocolate."

00:12:52.460 --> 00:12:54.320
MARTHA ORTIZ: "Like
Water for Chocolate."

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:57.410
Now, I'm very good friends of
Laura Esquivel because once,

00:12:57.410 --> 00:12:58.255
I--

00:12:58.255 --> 00:12:59.750
the [INAUDIBLE]
made this book that

00:12:59.750 --> 00:13:01.790
is called "Gritos y Sussuros."

00:13:01.790 --> 00:13:04.670
And I was beside her, and
I said, you don't know,

00:13:04.670 --> 00:13:09.260
but I am what I am because
of you, and she was, why?

00:13:09.260 --> 00:13:13.310
Because you built the
character in a woman

00:13:13.310 --> 00:13:16.950
that was a rebel through food.

00:13:16.950 --> 00:13:19.670
So in the movie,
what is beautiful is

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:23.150
if she was in love, everybody
was in love with the food.

00:13:23.150 --> 00:13:27.930
So I started believing that
food can have emotions.

00:13:27.930 --> 00:13:31.700
And if you're sad, everybody
is sad when it takes the food.

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:34.910
So feelings can
trespass the food.

00:13:34.910 --> 00:13:38.720
So everything has started
melting, you know?

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:41.000
Everything at the same time.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:47.090
And then Emanuele, my partner,
decide to go back to Paris

00:13:47.090 --> 00:13:49.601
because he was French.

00:13:49.601 --> 00:13:52.720
And I said, what I'm going
to do with this office?

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:55.590
I don't like to
charge the clients.

00:13:55.590 --> 00:13:57.140
I don't like that
kind of things.

00:13:57.140 --> 00:13:58.610
I love the creative part.

00:13:58.610 --> 00:14:06.770
So I remember that I married
an artist, my first marriage.

00:14:06.770 --> 00:14:08.840
I married a very
rebel artist that

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:10.732
was handsome, and nice, and--

00:14:10.732 --> 00:14:11.440
SPEAKER: Perfect.

00:14:11.440 --> 00:14:13.260
MARTHA ORTIZ: The
perfect fit, you know?

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:18.830
But in the moment that I told
him, I want to do something.

00:14:18.830 --> 00:14:22.430
he was very, very clear with me.

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:24.049
Yes, you're going
to work for me.

00:14:24.049 --> 00:14:25.340
That's what you're going to do.

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:27.830
And he gave me a book
that it was called,

00:14:27.830 --> 00:14:30.140
"The Wife of the
Artist," and it was

00:14:30.140 --> 00:14:35.300
horrible because all the wives,
they have miserable lives,

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:39.020
you know, miserable lives,
just some examples like

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:42.530
[INAUDIBLE] maybe that you have,
you know, the little thing.

00:14:42.530 --> 00:14:45.560
But they were horrible
lives, and I said,

00:14:45.560 --> 00:14:47.040
I don't want this life.

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:50.250
So I remember that I
went out of that house

00:14:50.250 --> 00:14:54.506
with just like 10 pesos,
no car, no nothing.

00:14:54.506 --> 00:14:55.380
SPEAKER: $0.30 today.

00:14:55.380 --> 00:14:56.838
MARTHA ORTIZ: Yes,
I remember that.

00:14:56.838 --> 00:14:58.620
I remember perfectly.

00:14:58.620 --> 00:15:00.570
And I went with
my mother's house,

00:15:00.570 --> 00:15:03.780
and I said, I have to
be here, I'm sorry,

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:07.570
maybe three, four months, but
I will go away another time.

00:15:07.570 --> 00:15:09.180
And she told me,
yes, of course, you

00:15:09.180 --> 00:15:11.100
can be here three
or four months.

00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:12.040
SPEAKER: Fantastic.

00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:12.780
MARTHA ORTIZ: Fantastic.

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:13.650
That's a true story.

00:15:13.650 --> 00:15:16.830
SPEAKER: It seems
that you talk of,

00:15:16.830 --> 00:15:18.821
you know, gastronomy like
almost as a language.

00:15:18.821 --> 00:15:19.820
MARTHA ORTIZ: Of course.

00:15:19.820 --> 00:15:22.890
SPEAKER: And I have seen
some of your interviews

00:15:22.890 --> 00:15:27.925
that you like to tell that
you're a writer in flavors.

00:15:27.925 --> 00:15:30.300
MARTHA ORTIZ: Of course, I
think that's the storytelling.

00:15:30.300 --> 00:15:32.700
SPEAKER: In your style,
I'd like delve a little bit

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:34.620
in your style.

00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:38.910
Artists usually say that part of
being a great artist is to find

00:15:38.910 --> 00:15:41.590
and inhabit your own style.

00:15:41.590 --> 00:15:45.120
Marcus Samuelsson recently said
that part of being a great chef

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:47.640
is to knowing who you are.

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:48.770
MARTHA ORTIZ: Of course.

00:15:48.770 --> 00:15:51.570
SPEAKER: So your style
is very unique, you know,

00:15:51.570 --> 00:15:53.610
from what you read in the
press, it's very bold.

00:15:53.610 --> 00:15:55.110
It's very feminine.

00:15:55.110 --> 00:15:59.100
It's very creative, but I think
it would be great for everybody

00:15:59.100 --> 00:16:00.960
to hear it from you, like--

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:02.260
MARTHA ORTIZ: What is my style?

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:03.718
SPEAKER: How would
you describe it?

00:16:03.718 --> 00:16:07.800
How would you-- and how
have you developed it?

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:10.680
How have you come to
find this is Martha?

00:16:10.680 --> 00:16:14.940
MARTHA ORTIZ: The first
thing is that I never

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:18.130
ever want to copy no one.

00:16:18.130 --> 00:16:22.870
The other thing that I adore
is showing that I'm a woman.

00:16:22.870 --> 00:16:27.240
I don't want-- I think there
is in the world, right now,

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:32.190
you know, the big chefs, they
have this minimalistic style,

00:16:32.190 --> 00:16:33.930
very masculine.

00:16:33.930 --> 00:16:34.770
And I say, I don't--

00:16:34.770 --> 00:16:39.817
I'm not-- I don't feel OK to
copy these and transport it

00:16:39.817 --> 00:16:41.040
to a dish.

00:16:41.040 --> 00:16:46.710
I adore these kind of
baroque, Mexican beauty.

00:16:46.710 --> 00:16:50.530
So and even I--

00:16:50.530 --> 00:16:55.500
I was talking this morning with
a very nice girl that I said,

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:59.550
I remember when I see all
the pseudorealistic painters

00:16:59.550 --> 00:17:03.360
and artists that live in Mexico,
like woman in Wonderland,

00:17:03.360 --> 00:17:10.170
you know Frida, Remedios
Varo, and Leonora Carrington,

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:13.140
this great photographer,
[INAUDIBLE],, the one

00:17:13.140 --> 00:17:15.290
with the big curls you know?

00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:16.859
And I said, this is fantastic.

00:17:16.859 --> 00:17:18.300
I want to be like them.

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:19.710
They were my role models.

00:17:19.710 --> 00:17:22.710
I never said I want to be
like the Joel Robuchon.

00:17:22.710 --> 00:17:30.140
I want to be like this artist
because they find the way.

00:17:30.140 --> 00:17:32.910
Imagine Frida because
everybody now sees Frida.

00:17:32.910 --> 00:17:38.010
She suffers a lot, everybody--
but finding her style being

00:17:38.010 --> 00:17:42.540
married with one of the most
important artists in the world

00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:43.600
at the--

00:17:43.600 --> 00:17:45.670
he painted this big
murals, and she decided

00:17:45.670 --> 00:17:47.690
to make these small paintings.

00:17:47.690 --> 00:17:52.020
And she was-- and that paintings
were her mural, you know?

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:54.960
She invented herself
like that's--

00:17:54.960 --> 00:17:56.610
that's what the exhibition said.

00:17:56.610 --> 00:17:59.550
And when you go to
Casa Azul of Frida,

00:17:59.550 --> 00:18:06.810
you really start feeling that
she invented the way that she

00:18:06.810 --> 00:18:10.520
wanted to be, but not
because of Diego, because

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:13.140
of her own [INAUDIBLE] with her.

00:18:13.140 --> 00:18:15.250
She used to adore animals.

00:18:15.250 --> 00:18:16.920
So she put the animals here.

00:18:16.920 --> 00:18:19.380
She adored to have, you
know, her big eyebrows,

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:21.360
and she never pulled it out.

00:18:21.360 --> 00:18:25.760
She put her-- her, you
know, the beautiful,

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:29.280
red nails and with the rings.

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:34.250
And his grand niece is a friend
of mine, Guillermo Kahlo,

00:18:34.250 --> 00:18:37.290
the photographer, he
always told me then

00:18:37.290 --> 00:18:40.200
when Frida went out on
the street, people laughed

00:18:40.200 --> 00:18:42.030
about her, imagining that--

00:18:42.030 --> 00:18:43.530
SPEAKER: Yeah, like
the appearance--

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:44.988
MARTHA ORTIZ:
--bourgeoisie society

00:18:44.988 --> 00:18:46.860
in Mexico in that
moment, looking

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:52.190
this woman going with
ribbons on the hair, strong.

00:18:52.190 --> 00:18:54.480
And she couldn't walk
very well because she

00:18:54.480 --> 00:18:55.620
had polio when she was--

00:18:55.620 --> 00:18:56.655
SPEAKER: Yeah, she
had-- and an accident.

00:18:56.655 --> 00:18:58.446
MARTHA ORTIZ: And an
accident called polio.

00:18:58.446 --> 00:19:00.960
She wanted, you
know-- and I said,

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:03.090
these women are fantastic.

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:05.310
I want to be a
woman in Wonderland,

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:06.520
in my own Wonderland.

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:10.020
So it was more personal.

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:12.390
And I developed-- and
I never want to see it,

00:19:12.390 --> 00:19:14.070
I say, this is in fashion.

00:19:14.070 --> 00:19:15.270
This is in trend.

00:19:15.270 --> 00:19:17.060
This is made by this male chef.

00:19:17.060 --> 00:19:19.440
And I said, no, I--

00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:20.700
I'm a woman.

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:21.780
I love lyrics.

00:19:21.780 --> 00:19:22.740
I love colors.

00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:26.550
I'm a proud Mexican,
and I'm trying

00:19:26.550 --> 00:19:33.720
to build a business with
a lot of women involved.

00:19:33.720 --> 00:19:36.520
I give the same opportunities
and sometimes a little bit more

00:19:36.520 --> 00:19:38.280
to the woman to
tell you the truth.

00:19:38.280 --> 00:19:41.160
If I have a man producer,
a woman producer,

00:19:41.160 --> 00:19:44.320
I say, let's see, bring
her first, you know?

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:46.870
Because for them,
it's very difficult.

00:19:46.870 --> 00:19:50.200
Imagine a lady who sells
tomatoes in Mexico.

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:55.120
It's very difficult to get to
a restaurant, to be a producer.

00:19:55.120 --> 00:19:59.710
So I have to be caring
about these type of things.

00:19:59.710 --> 00:20:01.150
I think so.

00:20:01.150 --> 00:20:03.160
SPEAKER: And for everybody
to know, I think,

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:06.850
there's a fantastic interview
from Martha with the "Evening

00:20:06.850 --> 00:20:08.560
Standard" in which she's--

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:12.086
you're credited with
saying you want to break--

00:20:12.086 --> 00:20:13.960
MARTHA ORTIZ: The caramel
ceiling, of course.

00:20:13.960 --> 00:20:14.500
SPEAKER: --the caramel ceiling.

00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:16.830
You want to help other women
to break the caramel ceiling.

00:20:16.830 --> 00:20:18.130
MARTHA ORTIZ: Of course,
I say the caramel

00:20:18.130 --> 00:20:19.930
because it's not the
glass ceiling for me.

00:20:19.930 --> 00:20:20.740
It's the caramel ceiling.

00:20:20.740 --> 00:20:22.630
SPEAKER: I think it's
a great topic on that.

00:20:22.630 --> 00:20:27.610
And I would like to hear
your thoughts on how--

00:20:27.610 --> 00:20:29.624
what does that mean for
you in your industry?

00:20:29.624 --> 00:20:31.540
MARTHA ORTIZ: These kind
of things-- you know,

00:20:31.540 --> 00:20:33.760
first I hate when they said--

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:37.907
and I'm very, you know, in the
opinion of Dominique Crenn,

00:20:37.907 --> 00:20:40.420
this great chef--

00:20:40.420 --> 00:20:42.670
it's horrible that
they say, this prize

00:20:42.670 --> 00:20:43.990
goes for the woman chef.

00:20:43.990 --> 00:20:45.590
I think that's horrible.

00:20:45.590 --> 00:20:46.900
It's not the best woman chef.

00:20:46.900 --> 00:20:47.740
It's the best chef.

00:20:47.740 --> 00:20:49.580
You don't have to
say it that way.

00:20:49.580 --> 00:20:52.180
You don't have to say it--

00:20:52.180 --> 00:20:54.820
let's make them happy.

00:20:54.820 --> 00:20:56.800
Let's say the best woman chef.

00:20:56.800 --> 00:20:58.420
I don't think that's fair.

00:20:58.420 --> 00:21:01.270
It's the best chef of the world.

00:21:01.270 --> 00:21:02.049
SPEAKER: True.

00:21:02.049 --> 00:21:04.090
MARTHA ORTIZ: And I think
if they start dividing,

00:21:04.090 --> 00:21:05.770
that's not nice.

00:21:05.770 --> 00:21:10.000
What I'm trying to do is
really to build opportunities

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.030
because maybe in Mexico--

00:21:13.030 --> 00:21:14.400
here it's different, maybe.

00:21:14.400 --> 00:21:19.360
But in Mexico, when
you have trainees,

00:21:19.360 --> 00:21:22.670
I try to educate and
be mentor of women

00:21:22.670 --> 00:21:24.910
and say, I have these 10 men.

00:21:24.910 --> 00:21:26.680
I have these six women.

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:29.500
Let's bring the women
first because they

00:21:29.500 --> 00:21:32.410
want to have an opportunity.

00:21:32.410 --> 00:21:34.780
They won't have it
maybe in other places.

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:40.630
Or they will be very small
windows or doors to open.

00:21:40.630 --> 00:21:41.860
So I'm trying.

00:21:41.860 --> 00:21:43.800
My pastry chef is a woman.

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:45.550
SPEAKER: Which is
fantastic, [INAUDIBLE]..

00:21:45.550 --> 00:21:48.030
MARTHA ORTIZ: I have one
sous chef man, one woman,

00:21:48.030 --> 00:21:52.210
and my head chef is a woman.

00:21:52.210 --> 00:21:56.260
And I'm trying, you know,
even with the flowers,

00:21:56.260 --> 00:21:58.250
I buy it from a woman.

00:21:58.250 --> 00:22:00.730
So I'm trying to make this
network that everything

00:22:00.730 --> 00:22:03.880
is, you know, very feminine.

00:22:03.880 --> 00:22:07.120
And because we don't have
opportunities in [INAUDIBLE]..

00:22:07.120 --> 00:22:10.180
SPEAKER: Do you
find that more chefs

00:22:10.180 --> 00:22:12.240
are following your example?

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:13.600
Do you see somebody--

00:22:13.600 --> 00:22:15.020
MARTHA ORTIZ: Yes, I
think they're-- they're--

00:22:15.020 --> 00:22:16.240
SPEAKER: --or do you
find yourself alone.

00:22:16.240 --> 00:22:17.387
MARTHA ORTIZ: There's
a wonderful woman chef

00:22:17.387 --> 00:22:18.340
that I adore.

00:22:18.340 --> 00:22:19.180
She's young.

00:22:19.180 --> 00:22:20.470
She's from Tabasco.

00:22:20.470 --> 00:22:22.990
Now she has a
restaurant in Mexico.

00:22:22.990 --> 00:22:25.780
And she always
called me, I'm making

00:22:25.780 --> 00:22:27.190
this name because of you.

00:22:27.190 --> 00:22:28.260
Can you help me?

00:22:28.260 --> 00:22:30.610
And I say, yes, of course,
because I put names

00:22:30.610 --> 00:22:31.910
to the dish that's different.

00:22:31.910 --> 00:22:37.520
I won't say, creme caramel with
the perfume of da, da, da, no.

00:22:37.520 --> 00:22:38.020
No.

00:22:38.020 --> 00:22:40.720
I call it Mary goes
to the flower shop

00:22:40.720 --> 00:22:42.940
because Mary is a character.

00:22:42.940 --> 00:22:44.380
And she changes every month.

00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:47.470
Even Mary has been
candidate and has lost.

00:22:47.470 --> 00:22:51.270
Sometimes she is fat, and she
doesn't want to be in the menu.

00:22:51.270 --> 00:22:51.770
You know?

00:22:51.770 --> 00:22:52.990
SPEAKER: She has her temper.

00:22:52.990 --> 00:22:54.531
MARTHA ORTIZ: Yeah,
she has a temper.

00:22:54.531 --> 00:22:55.580
She's a modern woman.

00:22:55.580 --> 00:22:58.330
She goes to the library.

00:22:58.330 --> 00:23:00.220
She wants to make a PhD.

00:23:00.220 --> 00:23:01.647
She's a modern woman, you know?

00:23:01.647 --> 00:23:02.230
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:23:02.230 --> 00:23:04.750
MARTHA ORTIZ: She's getting
divorced, so, please, you know,

00:23:04.750 --> 00:23:06.730
Mary has to take care of her.

00:23:06.730 --> 00:23:08.610
She's with the attorney.

00:23:08.610 --> 00:23:09.610
And everybody laughed.

00:23:09.610 --> 00:23:11.960
Now I'm making that book.

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:17.230
I have, I think, like,
14 emails from my editor

00:23:17.230 --> 00:23:20.380
because he's mad because I
have to do it more quickly.

00:23:20.380 --> 00:23:24.850
But this is a fantastic book
because the name is Maria,

00:23:24.850 --> 00:23:28.540
because I love the name
in Spanish, "Marie Va, "

00:23:28.540 --> 00:23:35.450
"Maria is Moving," "Recipes
for a Woman with Greatness."

00:23:35.450 --> 00:23:36.940
SPEAKER: Oh, I love that.

00:23:36.940 --> 00:23:37.440
I love that.

00:23:37.440 --> 00:23:40.680
MARTHA ORTIZ: So what I'm doing
is putting this-- it's not just

00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:42.400
like a gastronomy book.

00:23:42.400 --> 00:23:45.640
The first part is
talking about what

00:23:45.640 --> 00:23:48.190
ingredients you need in life.

00:23:48.190 --> 00:23:52.300
And the second part of the book
are my favorite women in Mexico

00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:55.450
that they tell the
recipe of their own life.

00:23:55.450 --> 00:23:58.360
So it's fantastic to see a
woman like Carmen Aristegui

00:23:58.360 --> 00:24:01.250
with a big knife and say, I
have to cut everybody, you know?

00:24:01.250 --> 00:24:03.700
And she gives a recipe
of little cookies.

00:24:03.700 --> 00:24:06.560
So it's this kind
of high contrast.

00:24:06.560 --> 00:24:07.327
So--

00:24:07.327 --> 00:24:09.493
SPEAKER: It sounds like a
fantastic project, Martha.

00:24:09.493 --> 00:24:12.280
MARTHA ORTIZ: It's going to be--
it's going to be the project.

00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:13.890
SPEAKER: You're more than
welcome to come back again.

00:24:13.890 --> 00:24:15.160
MARTHA ORTIZ: Yes, of course.

00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:15.960
SPEAKER: It will be a
privlege to have that.

00:24:15.960 --> 00:24:17.390
MARTHA ORTIZ: Yes, and
we need to bring these 12

00:24:17.390 --> 00:24:18.837
women that they are fantastic.

00:24:18.837 --> 00:24:19.420
You know them.

00:24:19.420 --> 00:24:20.290
SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:24:20.290 --> 00:24:22.081
MARTHA ORTIZ: And some,
they are, you know,

00:24:22.081 --> 00:24:25.090
very famous and the other
are not famous, but for me,

00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:26.650
are heroines.

00:24:26.650 --> 00:24:28.450
They are in the resistance.

